    "body": "<!-- Thank you for your contribution! Please follow these guidelines to enhance your pull request. If anything is unclear, submit your PR and reach out to maintainers for assistance. Join our Slack community at https://slack.sglang.io to discuss further. -->\r\n\r\n## Motivation\r\n\r\n\r\n### Background\r\n\r\nIssue #22291 reported significant accuracy degradation when using the `trtllm_mla` backend with chunked prefill to process multiple prompts in parallel on Blackwell GPUs. Benchmarks showed that certain sequences under `trtllm_mla` exhibited MSE values as high as 1.0–3.0, whereas the `fa4` and `flashinfer` backends produced MSE values consistently below 0.07 under identical conditions. Notably, the issue only manifested when processing multiple prompts concurrently (batch size > 1); single-request inference produced correct results.\r\n\r\n### Root Cause\r\n\r\nDeepSeek MLA compresses the KV cache into low-dimensional latent vectors. During prefill, these latents must be decompressed via `kv_b_proj` to recover the full multi-head K and V tensors. For long prefixes, performing this decompression all at once would exceed GPU memory, so a chunked strategy is employed: the prefix KV cache is decompressed and attended to in smaller chunks, with results merged incrementally via `merge_state`.\r\n\r\nWithin a single batch, different sequences may have different prefix cache lengths depending on their radix tree match results. The total number of chunks is determined by the longest prefix in the batch. Sequences with shorter prefixes will have exhausted their cached KV in earlier chunks, resulting in kv_len=0 for subsequent chunks. Under correct semantics, these rows should produce `out=0` and `lse=-inf`, allowing `merge_state` to safely ignore their contribution.\r\n\r\nHowever, the TRT-LLM ragged attention cubin kernel (invoked through FlashInfer) does not correctly handle the kv_len=0 edge case — stale data remains in the workspace's softmaxStats buffer, producing non-zero outputs and non-`-inf` LSE values. This corrupts the `merge_state` accumulation. This also explains why the issue only appears with concurrent multi-prompt inference — kv_len=0 only arises when prefix lengths differ across sequences within a batch.\r\n\r\n### Current Workaround (PR #22688)\r\n\r\nPR #22688 introduces a lightweight fixup kernel that runs after the TRT-LLM kernel call: for any rows where kv_len=0, it forces `out=0` and `lse=-inf`. A precomputed per-chunk CPU flag (`prefix_chunk_has_zero_kv`) ensures the fixup kernel is only launched for chunks that actually contain zero-KV rows, keeping overhead minimal. Ideally, the proper long-term fix would be for the TRT-LLM kernel itself to handle kv_len=0 correctly.\r\n\r\n### Root Cause Fix\r\n\r\nHere is the root cause fix for the FlashInfer TRT-LLM cubin kernel. Currently, when calling `trtllm_ragged_attention_deepseek` with a batch where some sequences have `kv_len=0` (but `q_len>0`), the cubin kernel produces incorrect results for those sequences — the output contains non-zero stale data and the LSE values are not `-inf`. The expected behavior for zero-KV sequences is `out=0` and `lse=-inf`, since there are no key-value tokens to attend to. This appears to be caused by uninitialized or residual data in the workspace's softmaxStats buffer within the cubin kernel. The issue surfaces in practice during chunked prefix cache attention, where sequences with shorter prefixes naturally have `kv_len=0` in later chunks. The incorrect LSE values then corrupt downstream `merge_state` operations, leading to significant accuracy degradation (MSE increasing from ~0.05 to ~3.0). A minimal repro would be to call the kernel with a two-sequence batch where one sequence has `kv_len=0`, and verify that its output rows are non-zero.\r\n\r\nFix #22291\r\n\r\n```\r\n  Doc 0 ( 10752 tokens): MSE = 0.021289\r\n  Doc 1 (  5909 tokens): MSE = 0.050858\r\n  Doc 2 (  2471 tokens): MSE = 0.059414\r\n  Doc 3 ( 18993 tokens): MSE = 0.006363\r\n  Doc 4 ( 12526 tokens): MSE = 0.064755\r\n  Doc 5 ( 20001 tokens): MSE = 0.000000\r\n  Doc 6 ( 15570 tokens): MSE = 0.016094\r\n  Doc 7 (  2781 tokens): MSE = 0.091810\r\n```\r\n\r\nReport: https://gist.github.com/yhyang201/3ffcf354b8bb1b6c6b3d4b045e83edb4\r\n\r\n## Modifications\r\n\r\n<!-- Detail the changes made in this pull request. -->\r\n\r\n## Accuracy Tests\r\n\r\n<!-- If this pull request affects model outputs (e.g., changes to the kernel or model forward code), provide accuracy test results. -->\r\n\r\n## Speed Tests and Profiling\r\n\r\n<!-- If this pull request impacts inference speed, provide benchmarking and profiling results. -->\r\n\r\n## Checklist\r\n\r\n- [ ] Format your code according to the [Format code with pre-commit](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#format-code-with-pre-commit).\r\n- [ ] Add unit tests according to the [Run and add unit tests](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#run-and-add-unit-tests).\r\n- [ ] Update documentation according to [Write documentations](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#write-documentations).\r\n- [ ] Provide accuracy and speed benchmark results according to [Test the accuracy](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#test-the-accuracy) and [Benchmark the speed](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#benchmark-the-speed).\r\n- [ ] Follow the SGLang code style [guidance](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#code-style-guidance).\r\n\r\n## Review and Merge Process\r\n\r\n1. Ping Merge Oncalls to start the process. See the [PR Merge Process](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/blob/main/.github/MAINTAINER.md#pull-request-merge-process).\r\n2. Get approvals from [CODEOWNERS](https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/blob/main/.github/CODEOWNERS) and other reviewers.\r\n3. Trigger CI tests with [comments](https://docs.sglang.io/developer_guide/contribution_guide.html#how-to-trigger-ci-tests) or contact authorized users to do so.\r\n   - Common commands include `/tag-and-rerun-ci`, `/tag-run-ci-label`, `/rerun-failed-ci`\r\n4. After green CI and required approvals, ask Merge Oncalls or people with Write permission to merge the PR.\r\n",
